Here's how to implement this in .NET MAUI Shell:

## 1. Override `OnBackButtonPressed` in your page

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            // Don't await — fire and forget since the method returns bool
            ShowUnsavedChangesDialog();
            return true; // Cancel default navigation
        }
        return base.OnBackButtonPressed();
    }

    private async void ShowUnsavedChangesDialog()
    {
        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard and go back?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (leave)
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

## 2. Custom "Cancel" back button in XAML

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.EditProductPage"
             Shell.BackButtonBehavior="{StaticResource CancelBackButton}">

    <ContentPage.Resources>
        <BackButtonBehavior x:Key="CancelBackButton"
                            TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </ContentPage.Resources>

    <!-- Or inline: -->
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}"
                           IconOverride="" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

## 3. ViewModel command for the custom button

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
private async Task Cancel()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool leave = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "Discard changes?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave) return;
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**

- `OnBackButtonPressed` handles the **hardware/swipe** back gesture (mainly Android).
- `Shell.BackButtonBehavior` with `Command` handles the **toolbar** back button and lets you customize its text/icon.
- You need both to fully cover navigation interception.
- Setting `IconOverride=""` (empty string) hides the arrow so only "Cancel" text shows.
